Repetitive negative thinking, self-reflection, and perceived cognitive dysfunction in older adults: a cross-sectional study
Discussion
The present study aimed to investigate the association between RNT, reflection, and subjective cognitive impairment in older adults, while considering the role of depressive symptoms. Consistent with our hypothesis, higher levels of RNT were associated with greater subjective cognitive dysfunction, independent of the contribution of depressive symptoms. In contrast, reflection did not exhibit a protective effect in general. However, it moderated the relationship between RNT and cognitive dysfunction, particularly when levels of reflection were below-average. This finding suggests that reflection alone may not be sufficient to buffer against the negative effects of RNT unless it is at an adequate level to facilitate effective problem-solving and emotional regulation. Theoretical frameworks support the observed associations between cognitive styles and cognitive dysfunction. Research on attention and memory biases in depression reveals consistent patterns across currently depressed, formerly depressed, and never-depressed individuals. Currently and formerly depressed individuals show attentional biases towards negative stimuli and away from positive stimuli [
27
]. RNT can act as a perseverative cognitive process that disrupts cognitive functioning by occupying cognitive resources and contributing to heightened emotional distress [
42
]. This aligns with our findings that higher levels of RNT are linked to greater cognitive dysfunction. Similarly, Zainal and Newman (2022) build on these ideas by proposing that the relationship between cognitive dysfunction and psychopathology symptoms, such as anxiety and depression, is bidirectional and complex [
17
]. Their review supports both vulnerability and scar theories, where cognitive dysfunction can both precede and result from anxiety-related symptoms. The observed associations in our study suggest that maladaptive forms of RNT, which may lead to cognitive overload and reduced cognitive efficiency, could contribute to subjective cognitive dysfunction [
43
]. Furthermore, our findings are consistent with the work of Sharp, Miller, and Heller (2015), who describe how transdiagnostic factors such as anxious apprehension and anxious arousal can influence executive function across multiple disorders [
16

